name: Saunter Canyon
description:
Introduction

The reef in the Northern Swell forms short, east-facing, wide canyons with potholes. Individually these canyons aren't headliners, but together they can make a fun desination and several can be descended in a day.

Saunter is a nice hike with interesting downclimbs and hike-arounds in a non-technical canyon environment. A longer day could be made of this and more technical canyon skills practice could be had.

Getting There

Drive to TH:

Option 1: From the exit on I-70 for Highway 24, head north on County Rd 1029 (S. Four Corners Mine Rd) up Buckmaster Draw for 4.8 miles. After a curve to the east, continue north on CR 1032 (South Buckmaster Rd) for 2.4 miles to the Junction of South Buckmaster Rd, North Buckmaster Rd and Smith Camp Rd.

Option 2: From I-70, drive north on US Hwy 6/191 for 4.7 miles and exit West onto County Road 1080 (Smith Camp/North Buckmaster Rd) for 2.25 miles to the same Junction.

From the Junction, continue west another 1250ft north on Smith Camp Rd and park on the south side before the old structures.

Approach

On Foot:

Walk through the old structures and walk upstream in the drainage. Take the fork that is Left Up Canyon and climb the sandstone domes north of the southern drainage on the north side.

Either hike to the top of Thimble Canyon and turn to the north to get to the top of Saunter Canyon or attempt an alternate approach that appears to be a shortcut (see kml map).

Descent

Hike downstream bypassing at least five potential obstacles.

Exit

Hike downstream back to the car.
